{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7ef8e3c2-c034-4acd-8a44-1ebf8d83b3bb","content":"## Debugging a C# MCP Server with MCP Inspector\n\n**1. Install & launch the Inspector:**\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\nThis opens a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:5173`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection:**\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Args:** `run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj`\n\n  Or if you have a built DLL:\n  - **Command:** `dotnet`\n  - **Args:** `exec /path/to/YourServer.dll`\n\n**3. Click \"Connect\"** — the Inspector spawns your process and communicates over stdin/stdout.\n\n**4. Debug your tools:**\n- Go to the **Tools** tab and click **List Tools** to see discovered tools.\n- Select a tool, fill in the input JSON, and click **Run Tool** to invoke it.\n- The **Notifications** pane shows server log messages (`notifications/message`).\n\n**Tips:**\n- Make sure your server only writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout**. Use **stderr** for any diagnostic logging (`Console.Error.WriteLine`), otherwise the Inspector can't parse the protocol stream.\n- If you need to attach a .NET debugger simultaneously, add a `Debugger.Launch()` call or `await Task.Delay(...)` at startup to give you time to attach.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"681cb0ea-526b-4d24-a638-ec07f2026d90","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to test and debug a C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling — I don't need to search the codebase for this. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":410,"requestId":"CBC2:350962:18B38D1:1BE8A80:69FE8940"},"id":"6fd675f1-432a-4696-b825-7fb0d18dc9b2","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:09:31.368Z","parentId":"1c48ce6c-7edd-4829-b37a-d3c921ad690f"}
